#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:19
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This guide introduces Docker, a lightweight virtualization solution to run "
"virtual units simultaneously on a single control host."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:29
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Docker is a lightweight virtualization solution to run multiple virtual "
"units (containers) simultaneously on a single control host. Containers are "
"isolated with Kernel Control Groups (<xref linkend=\"vle.docker.cgroup\"/>) "
"and <xref linkend=\"vle.docker.namespace\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:35
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Full virtualization solutions such as &xen;, &kvm;, or &libvirt; are based "
"on the processor simulating a complete hardware environment and controlling "
"the virtual machines. However, Docker only provides operating system-level "
"virtualization where the Linux kernel controls isolated containers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:43
#, no-c-format
msgid "Terminology"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:45
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following list contains important terminology and introduces you to "
"certain fundamental concepts of Docker."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: remark
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:48
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"taroth 2014-10-30: aginies, perhaps sort the terms alphabetically? like in a "
"glossary?"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:54
#, no-c-format
msgid "cgroups"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:56
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Control Groups is a Linux kernel feature that allows aggregating or "
"partitioning tasks (processes) and all their children into hierarchically "
"organized groups to isolate resources."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:64
#, no-c-format
msgid "Image"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:66
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A <emphasis>virtual machine</emphasis> on the host server that can run any "
"Linux system, for example &sls;, &sled;, or &opensuse;. A Docker image is "
"made by a series of layers built one over the other. Each layer corresponds "
"to a permanent change committed from a container to the image. For more "
"details, see the official Docker documentation at <link xlink:href=\"http://"
"docs.docker.com/engine/reference/glossary#image\"></link>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:76
#, no-c-format
msgid "Image Name"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:78
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A name that refers to an image. The name is used by the Docker commands."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:85
#, no-c-format
msgid "Container"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:87
#, no-c-format
msgid "A running Docker image."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:93
#, no-c-format
msgid "Container ID"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:95
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"An ID that refers to a particular container. The ID is used by the Docker "
"commands."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:102
#, no-c-format
msgid "<term>Tag</term>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:104
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A string associated with an image. It is commonly used to identify a "
"specific version of an image (similar to tags in version control systems). "
"It is also possible to refer to the same image with different tags."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:111
#, no-c-format
msgid "Kernel Namespaces"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:113
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Namespaces are a kernel feature to isolate some resources like network, "
"users, and others for a group of processes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:120
#, no-c-format
msgid "Docker Host Server"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:122
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The system that runs the Docker daemon, and provides images and management "
"control capabilities through <xref linkend=\"vle.docker.cgroup\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:130
#, no-c-format
msgid "Registry"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:132
#, no-c-format
msgid "A remote storage for Docker images."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:138
#, no-c-format
msgid "Repository"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:140
#, no-c-format
msgid "Place where all the versions of a Docker image are kept."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:146
#, no-c-format
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:148
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Docker is a platform that allows developers and system administrators to "
"manage the complete life cycle of images. Docker makes it easy to build, "
"ship and run images containing applications."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:155
#, no-c-format
msgid "Benefits of Docker"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:157
#, no-c-format
msgid "Isolation of applications and operating systems through containers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:162
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Near native performance, as Docker manages allocation of resources in real "
"time."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:166
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Controls network interfaces and resources available inside containers "
"through cgroups."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:172
#, no-c-format
msgid "Versioning of images."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:177
#, no-c-format
msgid "Allows building new images based on existing ones."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:182
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Docker Hub allows sharing and storing of images in public or private "
"repositories:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:188
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more information about public repositories, see <link xlink:href="
"\"http://docs.docker.com/docker-hub/\"></link>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:194
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more information about private repositories, see <link xlink:href="
"\"http://docs.docker.com/userguide/dockerrepos/#private-repositories\"></"
"link>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:204
#, no-c-format
msgid "Limitations of Docker"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:206
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Containers run inside the host system's kernel and cannot use a different "
"kernel."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:212
#, no-c-format
msgid "Only allows Linux <emphasis>guest</emphasis> operating systems."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:217
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Docker is not a full virtualization stack like &xen;, &kvm;, or &libvirt;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:223
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Security depends on the host system. Refer to the <link xlink:href=\"http://"
"docs.docker.com/articles/security/\">official security documentation</link> "
"for more details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:232
#, no-c-format
msgid "Container Drivers"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:233
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Docker uses <link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/docker/libcontainer"
"\">libcontainer</link> as the back-end driver to handle containers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:239
#, no-c-format
msgid "Storage Drivers"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:240
#, no-c-format
msgid "Docker supports different storage drivers:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:245
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<systemitem class=\"resource\">vfs</systemitem>: this driver is "
"automatically used when the Docker host file system does not support copy-on-"
"write. This is a simple driver which does not offer some advantages of "
"Docker (like sharing layers, more on that in the next sections). It is "
"highly reliable but also slow."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:254
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<systemitem class=\"resource\">devicemapper</systemitem>: this driver relies "
"on the device-mapper thin provisioning module. It supports copy-on-write, "
"hence it offers all the advantages of Docker."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:261
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<systemitem class=\"resource\">btrfs</systemitem>: this driver relies on "
"Btrfs to provide all the features required by Docker. To use this driver the "
"<filename>/var/lib/docker</filename> directory must be on a Btrfs file "
"system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:269
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<systemitem class=\"resource\">AUFS</systemitem>: this driver relies on the "
"AUFS union file system. Neither the upstream kernel nor the SUSE one "
"supports this file system. Hence the AUFS driver is not built into the SUSE "
"Docker package."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:276
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&slea;&nbsp;12 uses the Btrfs file system by default, which leads Docker to "
"use the <systemitem class=\"resource\">btrfs</systemitem> driver."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:280
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It is possible to specify which driver to use by changing the value of the "
"<envar>DOCKER_OPTS</envar> variable defined inside of the <filename>/etc/"
"sysconfig/docker</filename> file. This can be done either manually or using "
"&yast; by browsing to <menuchoice> <guimenu>System</guimenu> <guimenu>/etc/"
"sysconfig Editor</guimenu> <guimenu>System</guimenu> <guimenu>Management</"
"guimenu> <guimenu>DOCKER_OPTS</guimenu> </menuchoice> menu and entering the "
"<systemitem class=\"library\">-s storage_driver</systemitem> string."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:290
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, to force the usage of the <systemitem class=\"resource"
"\">devicemapper</systemitem> driver enter the following text:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:295
#, no-c-format
msgid "DOCKER_OPTS=\"-s devicemapper\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:297
#, no-c-format
msgid "Mounting <filename>/var/lib/docker</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:298
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It is recommended to have <filename>/var/lib/docker</filename> mounted on a "
"different file system to not affect the Docker host operating system in case "
"of a file system corruption."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:307
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting Up a Docker Host"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:312
#, no-c-format
msgid "General Preparation"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:313
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Prepare the host as described below. Before installing any Docker-related "
"packages, you need to enable the container module:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:319
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enabling the Container Module Using &yast;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:321
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Start &yast;, and select <menuchoice> <guimenu>Software</guimenu> <guimenu> "
"Software Repositories</guimenu> </menuchoice>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:327
#, no-c-format
msgid "Click <guimenu>Add</guimenu> to open the add-on dialog."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:332
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Select <guimenu>Extensions and Modules from Registration Server</guimenu> "
"and click <guimenu>Next</guimenu>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:338
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"From the list of available extensions and modules, select <guimenu>Container "
"Module 12 x86_64</guimenu> and click <guimenu>Next</guimenu>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:343
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The containers module and its repositories will be added to your system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:349
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you use &smtool;, update the list of repositories on the &smt; server."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:354
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enabling the Container Module Using SUSEConnect"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:356
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Container Module can be added also with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:359
#, no-c-format
msgid "$ sudo SUSEConnect -p sle-module-containers/12/x86_64 -r ''"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:361
#, no-c-format
msgid "Note about the SUSEConnect syntax"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:362
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>-r ''</option> flag is required to avoid a known limitation of "
"SUSEConnect."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:370
#, no-c-format
msgid "Installing and Setting Up Docker"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:372
#, no-c-format
msgid "Install the <systemitem>docker</systemitem> package:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:375
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo zypper install docker"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:378
#, no-c-format
msgid "To automatically start the Docker service at boot time:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:381
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo systemctl enable docker.service"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:382
#, no-c-format
msgid "This will automatically enable docker.socket in consequence."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:387
#, no-c-format
msgid "Start the Docker service:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:390
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo systemctl start docker.service"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:391
#, no-c-format
msgid "This will automatically start docker.socket in consequence."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:396
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The Docker daemon listens on a local socket which is accessible only by the "
"<systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> user and by the members of "
"the <systemitem class=\"groupname\">docker</systemitem> group. The "
"<systemitem class=\"groupname\">docker</systemitem> group is automatically "
"created at package installation time. To allow a certain user to connect to "
"the local Docker daemon, use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:404
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo /usr/sbin/usermod -aG docker <replaceable>USERNAME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:405
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The user can communicate with the local Docker daemon upon his next login."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:412
#, no-c-format
msgid "Networking"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:413
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you want your containers to be able to access the external network, you "
"must enable the <option>ipv4 ip_forward</option> rule. This can be done "
"using &yast; by browsing to <menuchoice> <guimenu>System</guimenu> "
"<guimenu>Network Settings</guimenu> <guimenu>Routing</guimenu> </menuchoice> "
"menu and ensuring <option>Enable IPv4 Forwarding</option> is checked."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:421
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This option cannot be changed when networking is handled by the Network "
"Manager. In such cases the <filename>/etc/sysconfig/SuSEfirewall2</filename> "
"file needs to be edited manually to ensure the <option>FW_ROUTE</option> "
"flag is set to <option>yes</option>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:427
#, no-c-format
msgid "FW_ROUTE=\"yes\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:430
#, no-c-format
msgid "Networking Limitations on Power Architecture"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:431
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Currently Docker networking has two limitations on the Power architecture."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:434
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The first limitation is about iptables. &slea;&nbsp;12 machines cannot run "
"Docker with the iptables support enabled. An update of the kernel is going "
"to solve this issue. In the meantime the Docker package for Power has "
"iptables support disabled via a dedicated directive inside of <filename>/etc/"
"sysconfig/docker</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:441
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"As a result of this limitation Docker containers are not going to have "
"access to the outer network. A possible workaround is to share the same "
"network namespace between and host and the containers. This however reduces "
"the isolation of the containers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:447
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The network namespace of the host can be shared on a per-container basis by "
"supplying the <option>--net=host</option> to the <option>docker run</option> "
"command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:453
#, no-c-format
msgid "iptables support on &slea;&nbsp;12 SP1"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:454
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&slea;&nbsp;12 SP1 hosts are not affected by this limitation but, given they "
"use the same &slea;&nbsp;12 package, they are going to have iptables support "
"disabled. This can be changed by removing the <option>-iptables=false</"
"option> setting inside of <filename>/etc/sysconfig/docker</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:462
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The second limitation is about network isolation between the containers and "
"the host. Currently it is not possible to prevent containers from probing or "
"accessing arbitrary ports of each other."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:471
#, no-c-format
msgid "Basic Docker Operations"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:473
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Images can be pulled from Docker's central index at <link xlink:href="
"\"http://index.docker.io\"></link> using the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:478
#, no-c-format
msgid "docker pull <replaceable>IMAGE_NAME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:480
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Containers can be started using the <command>docker run</command> command. "
"Refer to the official documentation of Docker at <link xlink:href=\"http://"
"docs.docker.com/\"></link> for more details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:487
#, no-c-format
msgid "Building Docker Images"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:489
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Starting with version 5.06.8, &kiwi; can be used to build Docker images. "
"Also see the official &kiwi; documentation, in particular <link xlink:href="
"\"https://doc.opensuse.org/projects/kiwi/doc/#chap.lxc\"></link>. The "
"official <systemitem>kiwi-doc</systemitem> package contains examples of "
"Docker images."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:497
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Docker has an <link xlink:href=\"http://docs.docker.com/reference/builder/"
"\">internal build system</link> which can be used to create new images based "
"on existing ones."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:504
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Some users might be confused about which build system to use for what task. "
"The recommended approach is to customize the official &slea; images for "
"Docker using the Docker build system. This approach has two advantages:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:513
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can use Docker-specific directives (like <literal>ENTRYPOINT</literal>, "
"<literal>EXPOSE</literal>, etc)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:518
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can re-use existing layers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:524
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Sharing the common layers between different images makes it possible to:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:530
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Use less disk space on the Docker hosts and on the remote registry service."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:536
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Deploy faster: only the requested layers are sent over the network (this is "
"similar to upgrading installed packages using delta RPMs)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:542
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Take full advantage of caching while building Docker images: this will "
"result in faster executions of the <command>docker build</command> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:550
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&suse; creates the official <link xlink:href=\"http://docs.docker.com/"
"reference/glossary/#base-image\">base images</link> using &kiwi; and "
"publishes them to allow customers to use those as foundation blocks inside "
"of the Docker build system. Only the Docker images built on top of our "
"official ones via the Docker build system are going to be supported."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:560
#, no-c-format
msgid "&sle; Images for Docker"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:562
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Currently we cannot distribute &slea; images for Docker because there is no "
"way to associate an End-User License Agreement (EULA) to a Docker image. "
"However, we provide official pre-built Docker images for &slea; and a "
"convenience tool called <link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/SUSE/sle2docker"
"\">sle2docker</link> that can be used to activate these images locally."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:571
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Pre-built images do not have repositories configured. But when the Docker "
"host has an SLE subscription that provides access to the product used in the "
"image, Zypper will automatically have access to the right repositories. For "
"more details see <xref linkend=\"sec.docker.sle_images.customizing_the_images"
"\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:578
#, no-c-format
msgid "Installing sle2docker"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:579
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <command>sle2docker</command> tool is part of the official container "
"module. It can be installed using the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:583
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo zypper install sle2docker"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:585
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Docker Daemon Needs to Be Running"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:586
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<command>sle2docker</command> requires the Docker daemon to be running on "
"the system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:594
#, no-c-format
msgid "Activating the Pre-built Docker Images"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:595
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The official pre-built Docker images for &slea; are shipped as RPM packages "
"inside of the <literal>containers</literal> module. They can be installed "
"using Zypper:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:600
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo zypper in sles11sp3-docker-image sles12-docker-image"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:601
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<command>sle2docker</command> can list the available pre-built images with "
"the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:605
#, no-c-format
msgid "sle2docker list"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:606
#, no-c-format
msgid "To activate a pre-built image, use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:609
#, no-c-format
msgid "sle2docker activate <replaceable>PRE-BUILT_IMAGE_NAME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:610
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"At the end of the activation, <command>sle2docker</command> will print the "
"name of the Docker image that has been created."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:617
#, no-c-format
msgid "Customizing the Images"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:618
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To create custom Docker images based on the official ones use <link xlink:"
"href=\"http://docs.docker.com/reference/builder/\"> Docker's integrated "
"build system </link>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:623
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The pre-built images do not have any repository configured. They contain a "
"<link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/SUSE/container-suseconnect\"> zypper "
"service</link> that contacts either the &scc; (SCC) or your Subscription "
"Management Tool (&smt;) server, according to the configuration of the &slea; "
"host that runs the Docker container. The service obtains the list of "
"repositories available for the product used by the Docker image."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:632
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You do not need to add any credentials to the Docker image because the "
"machine credentials are automatically injected into the container by the "
"docker daemon. They are injected inside of the <filename>/run/secrets</"
"filename> directory. The same applies to the <filename>/etc/SUSEConnect</"
"filename> file of the host system, which is automatically injected into the "
"<filename>/run/secrets</filename> file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:641
#, no-c-format
msgid "Credentials and Security"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:642
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The contents of the <filename>/run/secrets</filename> directory are never "
"committed to a Docker image, hence there is no risk of your credentials "
"leaking."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:648
#, no-c-format
msgid "To obtain the list of repositories use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:651
#, no-c-format
msgid "zypper ref -s"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:652
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It will automatically add all the repositories to your container. For each "
"repository added to the system a new file is going to be created under "
"<command>/etc/zypp/repos.d</command>. The URLs of these repositories include "
"an access token that automatically expires after 12 hours. To renew the "
"token call the <command>zypper ref -s</command> command. It is secure to "
"commit these files to a Docker image."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:660
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you want to use a different set of credentials, place a custom <filename>/"
"etc/zypp/credentials.d/SCCcredentials</filename> file inside of the Docker "
"image. It contains the machine credentials that have the subscription you "
"want to use. The same applies to the <filename>SUSEConnect</filename> file: "
"to override the file available on the host system that is running the Docker "
"container, add a custom <filename>/etc/SUSEConnect</filename> file inside of "
"the Docker image."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:670
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating a Custom &slea;&nbsp;12 Image"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:671
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following Docker file creates a simple Docker image based on &slea;"
"&nbsp;12:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:675
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"FROM suse/sles12:latest\n"
"\n"
"RUN zypper --gpg-auto-import-keys ref -s\n"
"RUN zypper -n in vim"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:676 vt_docker_quick.xml:689
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"When the Docker host machine is registered against an internal &smt; server, "
"the Docker image requires the SSL certificate used by &smt;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:680
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"FROM suse/sles12:latest\n"
"\n"
"# Import the crt file of our private SMT server\n"
"ADD http://smt.test.lan/smt.crt /etc/pki/trust/anchors/smt.crt\n"
"RUN update-ca-certificates\n"
"\n"
"RUN zypper --gpg-auto-import-keys ref -s\n"
"RUN zypper -n in vim"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:683
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating a Custom &slea;&nbsp;11 SP3 Image"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:684
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following Docker file creates a simple Docker image based on &slea;"
"&nbsp;11 SP3:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:688
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"FROM suse/sles11sp3:latest\n"
"\n"
"RUN zypper --gpg-auto-import-keys ref -s\n"
"RUN zypper -n in vim"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:693
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"FROM suse/sles11sp3:latest\n"
"\n"
"# Import the crt file of our private SMT server\n"
"ADD http://smt.test.lan/smt.crt /etc/ssl/certs/smt.pem\n"
"RUN c_rehash /etc/ssl/certs\n"
"\n"
"RUN zypper --gpg-auto-import-keys ref -s\n"
"RUN zypper -n in vim"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:698
#, no-c-format
msgid "Hosting Docker Images On-premise"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:700
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This section addresses some common questions like: what can be done with the "
"custom Docker images I created? How can they be shared within my "
"organization?"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:706
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The easiest solution would be to push these images to the Docker Hub. "
"However, there are a couple of important matters to keep in mind: By "
"default, all the images pushed to the Docker Hub are public. To keep them "
"private you need to pay a subscription-based fee. Moreover you do not have "
"control over the servers where your data is stored. This may not comply with "
"your organization's or company's policies to have full control over their "
"intellectual property. The solution to this problem is simple: To avoid the "
"use of Docker Hub, you can run an on-site Docker registry where to store all "
"the Docker images used by your organization or company."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:720
#, no-c-format
msgid "What is a Docker Registry?"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:721
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The Docker registry is an open source project created by Docker Inc. It "
"allows the storage and retrieval of Docker images. By running a local "
"instance of the Docker registry it is possible to completely avoid usage of "
"the Docker Hub."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:725
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The Docker registry is also used by the Docker Hub. However, the Docker Hub, "
"as seen from the user perspective, is made of the following parts at least:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:732
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The user interface (UI): The part that is accessed by users with their "
"browser. The UI provides a nice and intuitive way to browse the contents of "
"the Docker Hub either manually or by using a search feature. It also allows "
"to create organizations made by different users."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:739 vt_docker_quick.xml:747
#, no-c-format
msgid "This component is closed source."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:744
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The authentication component: This is used to protect the images stored "
"inside of the Docker Hub. It validates all push, pull and search requests."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:752
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The storage back-end: This is where the Docker images are sent and "
"downloaded from. It is provided by the Docker registry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:756
#, no-c-format
msgid "This component is open source."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:764
#, no-c-format
msgid "Installing and Setting Up Docker Registry"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:767
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Install the <systemitem>docker-distribution-registry</systemitem> package:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:771
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo zypper install docker-distribution-registry"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:774
#, no-c-format
msgid "To automatically start the Docker registry at boot time:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:777
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo systemctl enable registry"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:780
#, no-c-format
msgid "Start the Docker registry:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:783
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo systemctl start registry"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:786
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The Docker registry configuration is defined inside of <filename>/etc/"
"registry/config.yml</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:790
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"With the default configuration the registry listens on ports <literal>5000</"
"literal> and stores the Docker images under <filename>/var/lib/docker-"
"registry</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:796
#, no-c-format
msgid "Incompatible Versions of Docker and Docker Registry"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:797
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Docker registry version 2.3 is not compatible with Docker versions older "
"than 1.10, because v2 manifests were only introduced with Docker 1.10. As "
"Docker and Docker registry can be installed on different boxes, the versions "
"might be incompatible. If you experience communication errors between Docker "
"and Docker registry, update both to the latest versions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:809
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more details about Docker registry and its configuration, see the "
"official documentation at: <link xlink:href=\"https://docs.docker.com/"
"registry/\"></link>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:817
#, no-c-format
msgid "Limitations"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:818
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Docker registry has two major limitations:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:823
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It lacks any form of authentication. That means everybody with access to the "
"Docker registry can push and pull images to it. That also includes the "
"possibility to overwrite already existing images."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:830
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"There is no way to see which images have been pushed to the Docker registry. "
"You can <remark>taroth 2015-07-09: maybe replace \"can\" with \"need to\"?</"
"remark> manually take notes of what is being stored inside of it. There is "
"also no search functionality, which makes collaboration harder."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:840
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The next section is going to introduce Portus, the solution to all of the "
"problems above."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:847
#, no-c-format
msgid "Portus"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:849
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Portus is an authentication service and user interface for the Docker "
"registry. It is an open source project created by &suse; to address all the "
"limitations faced by the local instances of Docker registry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:855
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"By combining Portus and Docker registry, it is possible to have a secure and "
"enterprise ready on-premise version of the Docker Hub."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:860
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Portus is accessible for &slea;&nbsp;12 customers through the Containers "
"module. To install Portus, use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:865
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo zypper in Portus"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:867
#, no-c-format
msgid "In order to configure Portus properly, follow these steps:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:873
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"First of all, you should install Portus' dependencies if you haven't "
"already. This is thoroughly documented here: <link xlink:href=\"http://port."
"us.org/docs/setups/1_rpm_packages.html#portus-dependencies\"></link>. This "
"document will help you to get through the installation process, and it will "
"also warn you about some of the common pitfalls."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:883
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"After installing Portus and its dependencies, you need to configure your "
"instance. The initial setup of Portus is explained here: <link xlink:href="
"\"http://port.us.org/docs/setups/1_rpm_packages.html#initial-setup\"></"
"link>. When you are done with portusctl, you should modify some configurable "
"values before using Portus. This is thoroughly explained in this "
"documentation page: <link xlink:href=\"http://port.us.org/docs/Configuring-"
"Portus.html\"></link>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:895
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To apply the configuration changes, restart Apache (this is required after "
"each configuration change)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:902
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Finally, when entering Portus for the first time, you will be required to "
"enter some information about your installed registry. For details, see: "
"<link xlink:href=\"http://port.us.org/docs/setups/1_rpm_packages#the-default-"
"installation.html\"></link>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:910
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Portus setup is now complete and you can start using Portus."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_docker_quick.xml:916
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Currently, Portus is part of &suse;'s Docker offer as a technology preview. "
"For more information and documentation about Portus, see: <link xlink:href="
"\"http://port.us.org/\"></link>."
msgstr ""
